<TITLE> Soldiers, militants clash in Kashmir, 10 killed </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 SRINAGAR, India, Sun Mar 22, (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - A three-day gunbattle between Indian forces and militants in Kashmir has left at least 10 soldiers and rebels dead, the army said on Sunday, a day after it exchanged fire with Pakistan on the Kashmir border. An army spokesman said soldiers came under heavy fire after they surrounded a militant hideout in Shamsbari forest near the border with Pakistan on Friday. "The firefight is still continuing," said army spokesman Lieutenant Colonel J. S. Brar, adding that four soldiers, including an officer, and six separatists had been killed so far. The gunbattle raged while Indian and Pakistani soldiers exchanged fire on Saturday across a different stretch of their border, Brar said. Pakistan accused Indian forces of "unprovoked firing" and said it had lodged a protest with New Delhi. But an Indian army official blamed Pakistani troops of starting the firing, and said one Indian soldier was wounded. Cross-border firing in Kashmir has been rare since India and Pakistan agreed to a ceasefire along the Himalayan frontier in 2003, paving the way for a peace process the following year. The initiative moved sluggishly amid lingering mutual suspicion until New Delhi put a pause on that dialogue after attacks in Mumbai in November in which 166 people were killed by Islamist gunmen. India says the attackers were from a militant group set up with the support of Pakistani security agents to fight in Kashmir. Pakistan denies any link between any state agency and the Mumbai attackers and is investigating the assault on the 
